Using NHGIS in R

Justin Broubalow

4/3/2017

Introduction

Geospatial Data Abstraction Library (GDAL) is a computer software library for reading and writing raster and vector geospatial data formats. What were going to do is use GDAL to map census data after downloading and simplifying our spatial data. Luckily, we already have access to GDALs set of tools in the sf package for R. Both the census data and spatial data will come from the NHGIS, but there are two problems with the spatial data that dont make them immediately useable to us in R: 1) They are too big and 2) They are in the wrong projection. This tutorial will guide you through the process of being able to use NHGISs census data in R.

To do all this, well be using a combination of a web browser and R (and optionally a command line).

First, lets load the packages well be using.

library(sf)
library(leaflet)
library(tidyverse)

Downloading Census Data and Shapefiles from NHGIS

For this step well be using just a web browser.

  1. Go to NHGIS. Click Get Data.

  2. Choose the geographic levels and year of data you want.

  3. Choose the data table and corresponding GIS boundary file you want. This is your dataset and spatial data, respectively.

  4. Once you have everything you want, click Continue in the data cart. Review your data, and click Continue again.

  5. We want our table file structure to be comma delimited (which will give us a .csv file), and we want to give our download a description so we can easily identify it if were coming back often. Finally, click Submit.

  6. Youll be brought to a screen that shows your data extract downloads (after logging in). Download each of the files to a folder you can easily find later.

For the purpose of this tutorial, were going to be using state-level population data from the 1920 census and the corresponding shapefile.

Simplifying the Shapefile

The next step is to simplify the shapefile within the spatial data so that it is easier to manage and read into RStudio. We will do this step in our web browsers using Map Shaper and RStudio.

  1. Use the home screen to upload your spatial data to Map Shaper. You can upload the entire nhgis0002_shape.zip folder, and it will automatically extract the shapefile. Click Upload to do so.

  2. Now we want to simplify the lines of the map so that we reduce the files size. Do that by clicking Simplify in the top-right corner and sliding the Settings. Lower percentages mean fewer lines and smaller shapefile sizes. How much you want to simplify depends on the level of detail you need. I have simplified our map to 1 percent because were only interested in state boundaries.

  3. Now click Export in the top-right to download a folder that contains the new, simplified shapefile. Be sure to take note of the location to which its downloading.

  4. Replace the old, unsimplified shapefile with the new, simplified one that you just downloaded. Note that the size of the new shapefile is much smaller than the old one.

  5. Upload the .zip folder containing your new shapefile to RStudio. RStudio will automatically extract the .shp file and the other necessary files. Also upload to RStudio the folder containing the census data.

  6. Read in the shapefile and the census data (Note that Ive also renamed the NHGIS code A7L001 for the sake of clarity.

states_1920 <- st_read("US_state_1920.shp", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
## Reading layer `US_state_1920' from data source `/home/jbroubal/clio2/gdal-tutorial/US_state_1920.shp' using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## converted into: MULTIPOLYGON
## Simple feature collection with 51 features and 7 fields
## geometry type:  MULTIPOLYGON
## dimension:      XY
## bbox:           xmin: -6293288 ymin: -1329871 xmax: 2255854 ymax: 4591568
## epsg (SRID):    NA
## proj4string:    +proj=aea +lat_1=29.5 +lat_2=45.5 +lat_0=37.5 +lon_0=-96 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs
census_1920 <- read_csv("nhgis0002_csv/nhgis0002_ds43_1920_state.csv") %>% 
  rename(Population = A7L001)

Changing the Projection of the Shapefile

Now that weve simplified and read in the shapefile, we have to change its projection so that it will map our data properly. To do that this, we will use GDAL. Because we are working in RStudio, we have two ways of using GDAL, through a command line or through the st_transform() argument in the sf R package. The command line method requires some extra effort, especially on Windows, so we will use st_transform() instead.

Should you want to use the command line method, you would first need to install GDAL (Very complicated on Windows and less so on OSx or Linux) and use the ogr2ogr tool that is part of the GDAL set of tools. You would then run the command ogr2ogr output.shp -t_srs "EPSG:4326" input.shp

Just like in the mapping worksheet, we want to reproject our projection to EPSG 4326 using st_transform().

states <- states_1920 %>% 
  filter(!STATENAM %in% c("Alaska Territory", "Hawaii Territory")) %>% 
  st_transform(4326)

Now we proceed as we normally would to join the census data with the spatial data so that we can go on to make a data map.

states_with_data_1920 <- states %>% 
  left_join(census_1920, by = c("STATENAM" = "STATE"))

census_pal <- colorBin("OrRd",
                       domain = states_with_data_1920$Population,
                       bins = 7, na.color = "#808080")

leaflet(states_with_data_1920) %>% 
  addTiles() %>% 
  addPolygons(fillColor = ~census_pal(Population),
              fillOpacity = 1,
              color = "black",
              opacity = 1,
              weight = 1) %>% 
  addLegend("bottomright", pal = census_pal,
            values = ~Population, opacity = 1,
            title = "1920 Population")
